edu.ucla.sspace.graph

Class LinkClustering

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.ucla.sspace.graph.LinkClustering
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    WeightedLinkClustering

    public class LinkClustering
extends Object
implements Serializable
    An implmentation of the link clustering described in Ahn, Bagrow, and Lehman (2010). This algorithm is a multi-class clustering algorithm that instead of clustering the nodes in a graph according to their similarity with eacher, clusters the links connecting the nodes to reveal communities that connect the nodes. For full information on the algorithm see,
    • Yong-Yeol Ahn, James P. Bagrow and Sune Lehmann. Link communities reveal multiscale complexity in networks. Nature 466, 761â€“764 (05 August 2010). Available online here.
    This algorithm automatically determines the number of clusters based on a partition density function. Accordingly, the clustering methods take no parameters. Calling the cluster method with a fixed number of elements will still cluster the rows, but will ignore the requester number of clusters.

    Note that this class is not thread-safe. Each call to clustering will cache local information about the clustering result to facilitate the #getSolution(int) and #getSolutionDensity(int) functions. This class provides one configurable property:

    Property:
    Default: true
    If true, this property specifies the edge similarity matrix used by HierarchicalAgglomerativeClustering should be computed once and then kept in memory, which is the default behavior. If false, this causes the similarity of two edges to be recomputed on-the-fly whenever it is requester. By computing these values on-the-fly, the performance will be slowed down, depending on the complexity of the edge similarity function. However, this on-the-fly setting allows for clustering large graphs whose edge similarity matrix would not regularly fit into memory. It is advised that users not tune this parameter unless it is known that the similarity matrix will not fit in memory.

    Author:
    David Jurgens

      • getConnectionSimilarity

        protected <E extends Edge> double getConnectionSimilarity(Graph<E> graph,
                                              int keystone,
                                              int impost1,
                                              int impost2)
        Computes the similarity of the two edges as the Jaccard index of the neighbors of two impost nodes. The impost nodes are the two nodes the edges do not have in common. Subclasses may override this method to define a new method for computing edge similarity.

        Implementation Note: Subclasses that wish to override this behavior should be aware that this method is likely to be called by multiple threads and therefor should make provisions to be thread safe. In addition, this method may be called more than once per edge pair if the similarity matrix is being computed on-the-fly.

        Parameters:
        sm - a matrix containing the connections between edges. A non-zero value in location (i,j) indicates a node i is connected to node j by an edge.
        e1 - an edge to be compared with e2
        e2 - an edge to be compared with e1
        Returns:
        the similarity of the edges.a
